tures—from Spain, Iran, Ukraine, Greece, Croatia, and Algeria—and examines the interaction between immigrant networks and West German state institutions as well as the ways in which patterns of cooperation and conflict differ. This study demonstrates how the social consequences of mass immigration became intertwined with the ideological battles of Cold War Germany and how the political life and popular movements within these immigrant communities played a crucial role in shaping West German society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectsxHistory. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszGermany (West)xHistory. 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryy20th century. 0aCultural pluralismzGermany (West)xHistoryy20th century. 0aEinwanderung. 0aEthnic conflictxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnic conflictzGermany (West)xHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzGermany (West)xHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantsxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aImmigrantszGermany (West)xHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrantszGermany (West)xPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aMinoritiesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMinoritieszGermany (West)xHistoryy20th century. 0aOst-West-Konflikt. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745959640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857459596423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857459596/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  